Alligator, Mississippi<====>124659<====>Alligator, Mississippi   Alligator is a town in Bolivar County, Mississippi, United States. The population was 208 at the 2010 census.   In 2009, Tommie "Tomaso"  Brown was elected Alligator's first black mayor.  GeographyAccording to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of  , of which   is land and  , or 548%, is water.  DemographicsAs of the census of 2000,    there were 220 people, 77 households, and 58 families residing in the town. The racial makeup of the town was 2091% White, 7727% African American, and 182% from two or more racesThere were 77 households out of which 390% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 351% were married couples living together, 351% had a female householder with no husband present, and 234% were non-families. 234% of all households were made up of individuals and 104% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  In the town, the population was spread out with 391% under the age of 18, 45% from 18 to 24, 273% from 25 to 44, 168% from 45 to 64, and 123% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 29 years. For every 100 females there were 833 males. Males had a median income of $21,875 versus $14,063 for females. About 415% of families and 472% of the population were below the poverty line, including 693% of those under the age of eighteen and 353% of those sixty five or over. EducationAlligator is served by the North Bolivar School District. 